Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:08.339 --> 00:00:10.380
MALE SPEAKER: Hi, and
thank you for coming today.

00:00:10.380 --> 00:00:15.550
This is a great collaboration
between the Authors Discussion

00:00:15.550 --> 00:00:17.435
Group and the Food team.

00:00:17.435 --> 00:00:21.940
We have Chef Margarita here,
from Chihuahua, Mexico.

00:00:21.940 --> 00:00:25.970
Today we're talking, or she will
be discussing, various recipes

00:00:25.970 --> 00:00:28.510
from her book,
"Mexico-- the Cookbook,"

00:00:28.510 --> 00:00:32.800
which covers pretty much most
of the regions, or states,

00:00:32.800 --> 00:00:33.690
in Mexico.

00:00:33.690 --> 00:00:35.517
So without further
ado, Chef Margarita.

00:00:35.517 --> 00:00:37.100
MARGARITA CARRILLO
ARRONTE: Thank you.

00:00:37.100 --> 00:00:38.510
Thank you very much.

00:00:38.510 --> 00:00:40.930
Well, thank you very much.

00:00:40.930 --> 00:00:42.400
Good afternoon.

00:00:42.400 --> 00:00:45.530
I'm very glad to be here,
sharing with you all

00:00:45.530 --> 00:00:51.040
this experience from
living such a long time.

00:00:51.040 --> 00:00:58.450
And I will start
with telling you

00:00:58.450 --> 00:01:02.640
that this is a recipe from the
Yucatan, in which the marinade

00:01:02.640 --> 00:01:09.010
we're going to prepare can be
used in mostly any protein.

00:01:09.010 --> 00:01:12.390
It can be used with chicken,
with fish, with shrimp,

00:01:12.390 --> 00:01:15.030
with pork.

00:01:15.030 --> 00:01:20.246
It will be delicious prepared
with almost anything.

00:01:23.120 --> 00:01:26.900
We'll start with-- let me see.

00:01:26.900 --> 00:01:32.010
We'll use the heat,
but if I take it away

00:01:32.010 --> 00:01:41.640
from the plate, the heat, it
will not roast the banana leaf.

00:01:41.640 --> 00:01:43.730
So I'll turn it upside down.

00:01:48.240 --> 00:01:53.306
And you will see how
it changes color.

00:01:53.306 --> 00:01:53.980
Look.

00:01:53.980 --> 00:01:54.710
Look.

00:01:54.710 --> 00:01:55.910
Are you looking?

00:01:55.910 --> 00:01:56.410
Look.

00:02:00.550 --> 00:02:05.060
It turns bright green-- look.

00:02:07.770 --> 00:02:12.200
And it becomes flexible.

00:02:12.200 --> 00:02:13.120
Look how nice.

00:02:17.420 --> 00:02:17.920
Look.

00:02:22.240 --> 00:02:24.310
OK, and now it's flexible.

00:02:24.310 --> 00:02:26.550
Look.

00:02:26.550 --> 00:02:28.810
And it doesn't break.

00:02:28.810 --> 00:02:30.355
Otherwise, it breaks.

00:02:36.910 --> 00:02:42.160
We are going to prepare the
marinade, which is achiote.

00:02:55.340 --> 00:03:06.110
This achiote is annatto
seed dissolved in vinegar,

00:03:06.110 --> 00:03:10.150
and make a paste,
together with dry roasted

00:03:10.150 --> 00:03:22.330
garlics, fresh garlics, spices,
cinnamon, bay leaves, peppers,

00:03:22.330 --> 00:03:23.330
allspice berries.

00:03:27.360 --> 00:03:32.370
And we'll make it liquid
with orange juice.

00:03:35.730 --> 00:03:39.980
If we don't have sour orange
juice, as we use in Mexico,

00:03:39.980 --> 00:03:43.500
then you add the orange juice,
normal-- regular any orange

00:03:43.500 --> 00:03:45.450
juice-- and vinegar.

00:04:01.140 --> 00:04:02.950
OK, so this is ready.

00:04:02.950 --> 00:04:03.970
We'll add epazote.

00:04:13.510 --> 00:04:14.251
Sorry.

00:04:14.251 --> 00:04:14.750
OK.

00:04:19.200 --> 00:04:25.590
And we'll prepare
this with the fish,

00:04:25.590 --> 00:04:28.170
and we'll put it in
the refrigerator.

00:04:36.850 --> 00:04:41.980
And now we will
prepare the escabeche.

00:04:41.980 --> 00:04:43.747
OK, we need olive oil.

00:04:57.890 --> 00:05:04.220
The garlics-- they
have to be complete

00:05:04.220 --> 00:05:06.590
so people can see them
and take them off,

00:05:06.590 --> 00:05:07.770
if they don't want them.

00:05:28.950 --> 00:05:47.680
We'll add the cinnamon bark,
some peppers, some cloves,

00:05:47.680 --> 00:05:49.570
and some bay leaves.

00:05:52.438 --> 00:05:55.784
[SIZZLING]

00:05:58.190 --> 00:06:03.292
All these herbs
start protesting.

00:06:03.292 --> 00:06:04.999
And red onion.

00:06:15.280 --> 00:06:16.320
Very slightly.

00:06:16.320 --> 00:06:18.340
We don't want them to get brown.

00:06:28.570 --> 00:06:38.570
We'll add the
vinegar, the chiles.

00:06:49.080 --> 00:06:57.550
But we have to-- in order
to have the flavor, but not

00:06:57.550 --> 00:07:02.630
the heat, you have to make
little holes in the habanero.

00:07:14.070 --> 00:07:14.570
Mmm.

00:07:19.450 --> 00:07:21.610
And we'll add a
little bit of water.

00:07:54.490 --> 00:07:57.320
OK.

00:07:57.320 --> 00:07:58.280
Little bit of salt.

00:08:05.510 --> 00:08:08.460
And that's it.

00:08:08.460 --> 00:08:10.575
We have to leave this resting.

00:08:16.220 --> 00:08:17.480
OK, this is ready.

00:08:21.450 --> 00:08:24.350
Mmm, smells delicious.

00:08:31.450 --> 00:08:32.850
We leave this resting.

00:08:32.850 --> 00:08:35.970
So it will get a red color.

00:08:35.970 --> 00:08:40.080
If you want it more
red, you put the skin--

00:08:40.080 --> 00:08:44.020
you know, this paper-like skin
that the red onions have-- put

00:08:44.020 --> 00:08:48.010
them in a cheese cloth,
together with a slice of beet,

00:08:48.010 --> 00:08:54.430
tie it, and put it there,
so it will get bright red.

00:08:54.430 --> 00:09:00.220
Sometimes you are in a hurry,
so you don't have time to.

00:09:00.220 --> 00:09:01.380
OK, this is ready.

00:09:07.260 --> 00:09:08.860
Now we'll prepare the fish.

00:09:31.580 --> 00:09:33.190
Yeah, [SPANISH]?

00:09:33.190 --> 00:09:33.760
Is that all?

00:09:44.915 --> 00:09:47.830
OK.

00:09:47.830 --> 00:09:52.810
We'll have the fish, a
little bit of pepper.

00:09:55.850 --> 00:10:02.070
We use a lot of the
allspice berries,

00:10:02.070 --> 00:10:07.260
and it's the only spice
that is from Mexican origin.

00:10:07.260 --> 00:10:11.380
The rest is from a
lot of other places.

00:10:11.380 --> 00:10:19.930
And the American ambassador
we had at that time,

00:10:19.930 --> 00:10:25.090
when he discovered
it, he tasted it,

00:10:25.090 --> 00:10:33.520
named it allspice, because
in its little berry

00:10:33.520 --> 00:10:36.860
it has the flavor of the
black pepper, the nutmeg,

00:10:36.860 --> 00:10:40.650
the cinnamon, and the clove.

00:10:40.650 --> 00:10:44.830
That's why it's called allspice.

00:10:44.830 --> 00:10:52.570
So we have onion, tomato.

00:11:07.010 --> 00:11:38.262
[INAUDIBLE] And we will
add a little more salt/

00:11:38.262 --> 00:11:40.870
Little bit of habanero.

00:11:40.870 --> 00:11:49.710
If you don't want habanero,
just omit it, or put one whole,

00:11:49.710 --> 00:11:52.740
without opening it, so
it will give the flavor,

00:11:52.740 --> 00:11:54.820
and it will not give the heat.

00:11:54.820 --> 00:11:55.320
OK?

00:12:08.710 --> 00:12:10.970
That's it.

00:12:10.970 --> 00:12:14.960
We can send it to be baked.

00:12:14.960 --> 00:12:18.970
And this, if you don't
have an oven, no excuse.

00:12:18.970 --> 00:12:20.440
You put it on a comal.

00:12:20.440 --> 00:12:24.800
You don't have a
comal, a saute pan.

00:12:24.800 --> 00:12:29.530
Put it on a saute pan,
like this, put a few drops,

00:12:29.530 --> 00:12:31.940
like an ounce of
water on the bottom

00:12:31.940 --> 00:12:36.280
so it creates the first
steam, and then cover it.

00:12:36.280 --> 00:12:41.010
It will be ready in 15
minutes, 10 minutes.

00:12:41.010 --> 00:12:41.890
That's it.

00:12:41.890 --> 00:12:46.816
We have it finished,
so that-- OK, OK.

00:12:46.816 --> 00:12:47.315
Questions?

