Come to Mexico.

00:13:04.470 --> 00:13:08.520
I would love to be in LA,
because my son is here, but no.

00:13:08.520 --> 00:13:10.790
He works for the movie industry.

00:13:10.790 --> 00:13:11.930
But no, no, no.

00:13:11.930 --> 00:13:14.487
In Mexico.

00:13:14.487 --> 00:13:15.362
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:13:21.150 --> 00:13:24.142
MARGARITA CARRILLO ARRONTE: I
would be a liar if I told you.

00:13:26.800 --> 00:13:28.400
But I'm going to
tell you something.

00:13:30.920 --> 00:13:37.450
If they give you something with
yellow cheese, don't eat it.

00:13:37.450 --> 00:13:39.550
We don't even have it in Mexico.

00:13:39.550 --> 00:13:42.870
We call it American cheese.

00:13:42.870 --> 00:13:46.240
So they have to be honest.

00:13:46.240 --> 00:13:52.530
They have to give you-- they
know that you like fried food,

00:13:52.530 --> 00:13:55.650
so that's why they-- and
of course, taquitos and all

00:13:55.650 --> 00:13:58.900
these things fried
are delicious,

00:13:58.900 --> 00:14:01.280
but it's not the only thing.

00:14:01.280 --> 00:14:08.010
You know, I normally never,
never fry the food I eat.

00:14:08.010 --> 00:14:11.260
But I try it in my menu.

00:14:11.260 --> 00:14:14.420
I have nothing fried but the
totopos that I-- we fry it

00:14:14.420 --> 00:14:16.610
every day, and
then after frying,

00:14:16.610 --> 00:14:19.120
I put them in the oven
with lots of kitchen paper

00:14:19.120 --> 00:14:21.660
so they let all the oil off.

00:14:25.210 --> 00:14:30.660
Because it has a very bad
fame of being unhealthy food.

00:14:30.660 --> 00:14:31.290
And it isn't.

00:14:31.290 --> 00:14:33.320
It's not fair.

00:14:33.320 --> 00:14:37.640
And there is a reason
why I understand.

00:14:37.640 --> 00:14:41.290
At the beginning, I was very
angry with Mexican people who

00:14:41.290 --> 00:14:45.260
cross the border,
and for me, it's

00:14:45.260 --> 00:14:47.400
a way of prostituting the food.

00:14:47.400 --> 00:14:50.490
They do prostitute the food.

00:14:50.490 --> 00:14:58.190
But I understood that they come
here searching for a better way

00:14:58.190 --> 00:15:01.880
to live, because in Mexico
they cannot find it.

00:15:01.880 --> 00:15:03.520
We are too many.

00:15:03.520 --> 00:15:08.210
And they come here,
they work hard,

00:15:08.210 --> 00:15:10.580
and they open these
little places,

00:15:10.580 --> 00:15:14.800
and they want to
be accepted madly.

00:15:14.800 --> 00:15:16.740
They need to be accepted.

00:15:16.740 --> 00:15:21.550
So they are willing to
adapt their traditional food

00:15:21.550 --> 00:15:23.660
to the American taste.

00:15:23.660 --> 00:15:26.480
So that's why they
do it, because it's

00:15:26.480 --> 00:15:30.930
the easier-- they didn't
come here to educate you.

00:15:30.930 --> 00:15:34.970
They came here to be accepted,
and to work hard, and to have

00:15:34.970 --> 00:15:36.230
a better life.

00:15:36.230 --> 00:15:41.200
So that's why they are willing
to prostitute the food,

00:15:41.200 --> 00:15:43.720
but I don't.

00:15:43.720 --> 00:15:52.300
So that's why I wrote this
book, and in many-- there

00:15:52.300 --> 00:15:56.070
are a few fried
recipes, like bunuelos,

00:15:56.070 --> 00:16:00.250
and other things, some desserts.

00:16:00.250 --> 00:16:04.480
But mainly,
everything-- you know,

00:16:04.480 --> 00:16:06.700
the traditional
cooking techniques

00:16:06.700 --> 00:16:11.500
of Mexican authentic food
is on the comal, steamed,

00:16:11.500 --> 00:16:18.480
boiled, in the pit,
through a hole in the oven,

00:16:18.480 --> 00:16:21.090
on hot stones.

00:16:21.090 --> 00:16:25.394
There are many other-- grilled--
many other ways, but not fried.

00:16:29.001 --> 00:16:29.876
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:16:52.820 --> 00:16:55.050
MARGARITA CARRILLO ARRONTE:
Well, to begin with,

00:16:55.050 --> 00:16:59.150
they don't find the
same ingredients.

00:16:59.150 --> 00:17:02.060
It's the most important reason.

00:17:02.060 --> 00:17:04.640
And something else.

00:17:04.640 --> 00:17:06.480
This is-- and you
will understand this.

00:17:06.480 --> 00:17:09.030
You're young, intelligent guys.

00:17:09.030 --> 00:17:14.609
You will understand that
when the Spaniards came,

00:17:14.609 --> 00:17:16.420
they brought the pigs with them.

00:17:16.420 --> 00:17:19.290
They brought the lard, and
they brought the olive oil,

00:17:19.290 --> 00:17:21.700
and the frying technique.

00:17:21.700 --> 00:17:23.440
And it was expensive.

00:17:23.440 --> 00:17:25.810
Mexicans couldn't afford it.

00:17:25.810 --> 00:17:28.030
Only rich people
could afford it.

00:17:28.030 --> 00:17:34.660
So it became a way of
status, a sign of status.

00:17:34.660 --> 00:17:39.515
Only rich people could
eat with these elements.

00:17:42.220 --> 00:17:48.610
There is even a saying in
Mexico, from colonial times,

00:17:48.610 --> 00:17:51.920
that when you haven't seen a
friend for a long time-- oh,

00:17:51.920 --> 00:17:54.520
have you seen Chochito Perez?

00:17:54.520 --> 00:17:55.020
Oh, no.

00:17:55.020 --> 00:17:59.070
But you know, they
even cook with lard?

00:17:59.070 --> 00:18:03.700
They are doing so well that
they even cook with lard.

00:18:03.700 --> 00:18:07.990
So it became like they
are so wealthy now,

00:18:07.990 --> 00:18:09.650
why, they can cook with lard.

00:18:09.650 --> 00:18:12.040
And that has happened here, too.

00:18:12.040 --> 00:18:15.250
When they come here,
they have a better life,

00:18:15.250 --> 00:18:18.130
and they can cook with oil.

00:18:18.130 --> 00:18:23.130
So the most remembered
things-- you know,

00:18:23.130 --> 00:18:26.400
food is completely
mingled-- Mexican food

00:18:26.400 --> 00:18:29.260
is completely mingled with the
culture, with the religion,

00:18:29.260 --> 00:18:33.030
and especially is
with the feelings.

00:18:33.030 --> 00:18:35.350
When you are sick,
you immediately

00:18:35.350 --> 00:18:38.590
remember what your mother cooked
for you when you were young.

00:18:38.590 --> 00:18:39.585
You were little.

00:18:39.585 --> 00:18:40.460
You remember it well.

00:18:40.460 --> 00:18:44.170
So food, as it becomes
something mixed

00:18:44.170 --> 00:18:49.680
with the feelings, and
the homesickness, and all

00:18:49.680 --> 00:18:55.240
these things-- they want
the most popular street food

00:18:55.240 --> 00:19:00.410
that reminds them of the food
from Chiapas, or from wherever

00:19:00.410 --> 00:19:01.364
they are.

00:19:01.364 --> 00:19:02.874
So they cook.

00:19:02.874 --> 00:19:03.749
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:19:07.230 --> 00:19:08.730
MARGARITA CARRILLO
ARRONTE: Achiote?

00:19:08.730 --> 00:19:09.480
Annatto.

00:19:09.480 --> 00:19:15.750
It's a bush that gives
a bright, red flower.

00:19:15.750 --> 00:19:22.020
But in the heart of it has
like a pod, like an open pod.

00:19:22.020 --> 00:19:25.310
And you open this
pod, and inside it's

00:19:25.310 --> 00:19:28.630
like a corn kernel,
a little corn kernel.

00:19:28.630 --> 00:19:33.360
And instead of white kernels,
it has red bright kernels.

00:19:33.360 --> 00:19:35.860
And it's the annatto seeds.

00:19:35.860 --> 00:19:37.830
And everybody
there, what they do

00:19:37.830 --> 00:19:42.180
is put them in a jar with
vinegar or sour orange juice,

00:19:42.180 --> 00:19:43.695
and let them soak.

00:19:43.695 --> 00:19:45.990
But they are going to use them.

00:19:45.990 --> 00:19:55.110
They mix them with dry roasted
garlic, cinnamon, black pepper,

00:19:55.110 --> 00:19:57.110
with spices.

00:19:57.110 --> 00:19:59.722
And they have their achiote.

